SIMPLE: frustrate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frustrate
<hw>Frus"trate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>frustratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>frustrare</ets>,
<ets>frustrari</ets>, to deceive, frustrate, fr. <ets>frustra</ets> in
vain, witout effect, in erorr, prob. for <ets>frudtra</ets> and akin to
<ets>fraus</ets>, E. <ets>fraud</ets>.]</ety> <def>Vain; ineffectual;
useless; unprofitable; null; void; nugatory; of no effect.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Our <xex>frustrate</xex> search.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frustrate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frustrate
<hw>Frus"trate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Frustrated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Frustrating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring
to nothing; to prevent from attaining a purpose; to disappoint; to
defeat; to baffle; <as>as, to <ex>frustrate</ex> a plan, design, or
attempt; to <ex>frustrate</ex> the will or purpose.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall the adversary thus obtain⟦br⟧
His end and <qex>frustrate</qex> thine ?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make null; to nullify; to render invalid or of no
effect; <as>as, to <ex>frustrate</ex> a conveyance or
deed</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To balk; thwart; foil; baffle; defeat.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frustrately</ent>⟦br⟧
